    {
        "title": "Crying in H Mart",
        "author": "Michelle Zauner",
        "date_display": "February 27, 2026",
        "date_sort": "2026-02-27",
        "review": "parts of it felt really self-centered and indulgent, but considering anyone at the age of 25 experiencing the loss of their significant other would probably be as panic and resentful.<br/>Overall it was a great read. I was reminded of my youth, listening to Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Karen O, going to live houses, allowing myself a mental rebel through (not so) underground music. <br/>I also enjoyed the parts describing how we seeing our mothers as strangers through cherished artifacts. It was only after making my grandmother a commemorating video did I know so much about her past through her innumerable photos. She came to me as was, but i have very little context and had very little imagination. How did we end up realizing how little we know about the people we care about? Moreover, how did we end up knowing how well our mothers have known about us? since the beginning, since when I couldn't trace back anymore.",
