    {
        "title": "The Year of Magical Thinking",
        "author": "Joan Didion",
        "date_display": "March 21, 2025",
        "date_sort": "2025-03-21",
        "review": "In an attempt to write with clarity and restraint, Didion delivered a piece with immense intimate detail of her grieving process over her husband. Trying her very best to maintain collectives, she writes in styles of journalism, reports, and dropping immense details of location, people, time, memories of seemingly irrelevant events, literature extracts, and medical terms. <br/><br/>Despite many reviews arguing that those ‘name-dropping’ of celebrities contributed little to her point, besides flexing on her apparently affluent and privileged life in wealthy neighborhoods in NYC and LA, I still found resonance in her writings.<br/><br/>To understand her piece, you have to see beyond that appearance of flamboyant reports. You have to see, with empathy, how those are in fact self-soothing acts, or her final resort to make sense of sickness and death, and hence our existence.<br/><br/>It was obvious that her life experience has shaped her as a cool, bright, arrogant, or even controlling figure and vice versa. Yet that stark and sharp style of narrating what had happened precisely gave her a unique way of processing that difficult emotion, while simultaneously reflecting a piece of underlying self-doubt and fragility that is truly universal in all of us.",
        "rating": "5",
        "cover": "https://books.google.com/books/content?id=MOJZ8ihldbAC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=0&source=gbs_api",
        "pages": "227.0",
