        "date_display": "",
        "date_sort": "0000-00-00",
        "review": "Translating Myself and Others is a more academic-like, fragmented yet investigative collections on translation, Lahiri's relationship with translation, and on discovered metaphors of transformation. <br/>A lot of criticism of this book talks about how she threw literary jargons around, basically criticizing her on \"flexing\" her experience and background in translation, basically condemning this book for not being democratic enough.<br/><br/>I personally would dispute these sort of comments, since I believe writings and art does not need to serve the public, but the readings of this collection would be way more meaningful if you do have literary training or are familiar with the authors Lahiri is writing about. <br/><br/>I think her writings resonates with anyone who \"lives\" with more than one language - when the identification of oneself ruptured with a single culture, and we seek and look to another place that we comfortably embrace as ours.",
